## 31. Common Mistakes

### Removing Too Many Rows

```python
cleaned = data.dropna()
```

This removes any row containing any missing value.

A large part of the dataset may be lost.

---

### Filling Every Missing Value with Zero

```python
data = data.fillna(0)
```

This may incorrectly mean:

```text
Missing salary → salary equals zero
Missing age → age equals zero
Missing rating → rating equals zero
```

Zero is a real value, not a universal missing-value replacement.

---

### Removing Every Outlier

An outlier may be:

* A valid high-value customer
* A real fraud case
* An important rare event

Deleting it automatically may remove the most useful observations.

---

### Cleaning Without Keeping Raw Data

Overwriting the only copy makes mistakes difficult to reverse.

Keep:

```text
raw_data
cleaned_data
```

separately.

---

### Using the Mean with Extreme Values

The mean may be distorted by outliers.

The median may be more suitable.

---

### Ignoring Data Types

A column may look numerical while actually being text.

Always inspect:

```python
print(data.dtypes)
```

---

### Treating Different People as Duplicates

Removing duplicates using only names is unsafe:

```python
data.drop_duplicates(
    subset=["name"]
)
```

Different people can have the same name.

---

### Data Leakage

Do not calculate cleaning statistics using test data before model training.

